ms", :type :wiki-api.core/category} #{951616 210356 1014301}, 1061435 #{}, {:id 20677277, :title "Hardness of approximation", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{861574 209939}, 3693563 #{}, 3309692 #{}, 3552444 #{}, {:id 263321, :title "Concave function", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1013956 272912 3552444}, 3539900 #{}, 951325 #{}, {:id 7500026, :title "Second-order cone programming", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1013280 1013956 2892114}, 838877 #{}, {:id 245568, :title "Convex function", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1013280 1013348}, 1014301 #{}, {:id 50263, :title "Domain of a function", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1278976 2870961}, 972862 #{}, 3130558 #{}, {:id 1560090, :title "Active set", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1321155 814884}, {:id 999701, :title "Rate of convergence", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1013280 2892114}, 3552447 #{}, {:id 456580, :title "Branch and bound", :type :wiki-api.core/article} #{1013956 3481365 951325}, 3614367 #{}, 1014463 #{}, 3547007 #{}}}, :doc-map {1278976 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1278976, :key "journals/mor/HuangZ07", :title "Complex Matrix Decomposition and Quadratic Programming.", :abstract "This paper studies the possibilities of the linear matrix inequality characterization of the matrix cones formed by nonnegative complex Hermitian quadratic functions over specific domains in the complex space. In its real-case analog, such studies were conducted in Sturm and Zhang [Sturm, J. F., S. Zhang. 2003. On cones of nonnegative quadratic functions. Math. Oper. Res.28 246--267]. In this paper it is shown that stronger results can be obtained for the complex Hermitian case. In particular, we show that the matrix rank-one decomposition result of Sturm and Zhang [Sturm, J. F., S. Zhang. 2003. On cones of nonnegative quadratic functions. Math. Oper. Res.28 246--267] can be strengthened for the complex Hermitian matrices. As a consequence, it is possible to characterize several new matrix co-positive cones (over specific domains) by means of linear matrix inequality. As examples of the potential application of the new rank-one decomposition result, we present an upper bound on the lowest rank among all the optimal solutions for a standard complex semidefinite programming (SDP) problem, and offer alternative proofs for a result of Hausdorff [Hausdorff, F. 1919. Der Wertvorrat einer Bilinearform. Mathematische Zeitschrift3 314--316] and a result of Brickman [Brickman, L. 1961. On the field of values of a matrix. Proc. Amer. Math. Soc.12 61--66] on the joint numerical range.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 601713, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yongwei Huang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 71480, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shuzhong Zhang"}), :year 2007, :venue "Math. Oper. Res.", :ncit 76, :string "Complex Matrix Decomposition and Quadratic Programming.. This paper studies the possibilities of the linear matrix inequality characterization of the matrix cones formed by nonnegative complex Hermitian quadratic functions over specific domains in the complex space. In its real-case analog, such studies were conducted in Sturm and Zhang [Sturm, J. F., S. Zhang. 2003. On cones of nonnegative quadratic functions. Math. Oper. Res.28 246--267]. In this paper it is shown that stronger results can be obtained for the complex Hermitian case. In particular, we show that the matrix rank-one decomposition result of Sturm and Zhang [Sturm, J. F., S. Zhang. 2003. On cones of nonnegative quadratic functions. Math. Oper. Res.28 246--267] can be strengthened for the complex Hermitian matrices. As a consequence, it is possible to characterize several new matrix co-positive cones (over specific domains) by means of linear matrix inequality. As examples of the potential application of the new rank-one decomposition result, we present an upper bound on the lowest rank among all the optimal solutions for a standard complex semidefinite programming (SDP) problem, and offer alternative proofs for a result of Hausdorff [Hausdorff, F. 1919. Der Wertvorrat einer Bilinearform. Mathematische Zeitschrift3 314--316] and a result of Brickman [Brickman, L. 1961. On the field of values of a matrix. Proc. Amer. Math. Soc.12 61--66] on the joint numerical range.", :doc-id "Complex Matrix Decomposition and Quadratic Programming. 2007  ,  "}, 951616 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 951616, :key "journals/jacm/Skutella01", :title "Convex quadratic and semidefinite programming relaxations in scheduling.", :abstract "We consider the problem of scheduling unrelated parallel machines subject to release dates so as to minimize the total weighted completion time of jobs. The main contribution of this paper is a provably good convex quadratic programming relaxation of strongly polynomial size for this problem. The best previously known approximation algorithms are based on LP relaxations in time- or interval-indexed variables. Those LP relaxations, however, suffer from a huge number of variables. As a result of the convex quadratic programming approach we can give a very simple and easy to analyze 2-approximation algorithm which can be further improved to performance guarantee 3/2 in the absence of release dates. We also consider preemptive scheduling problems and derive approximation algorithms and results on the power of preemption which improve upon the best previously known results for these settings. Finally, for the special case of two machines we introduce a more sophisticated semidefinite programming relaxation and apply the random hyperplane technique introduced by Goemans and Williamson for the MaxCut problem; this leads to an improved 1.2752-approximation.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 642352, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Martin Skutella"}), :year 2001, :venue "J. ACM", :ncit 102, :string "Convex quadratic and semidefinite programming relaxations in scheduling.. We consider the problem of scheduling unrelated parallel machines subject to release dates so as to minimize the total weighted completion time of jobs. The main contribution of this paper is a provably good convex quadratic programming relaxation of strongly polynomial size for this problem. The best previously known approximation algorithms are based on LP relaxations in time- or interval-indexed variables. Those LP relaxations, however, suffer from a huge number of variables. As a result of the convex quadratic programming approach we can give a very simple and easy to analyze 2-approximation algorithm which can be further improved to performance guarantee 3/2 in the absence of release dates. We also consider preemptive scheduling problems and derive approximation algorithms and results on the power of preemption which improve upon the best previously known results for these settings. Finally, for the special case of two machines we introduce a more sophisticated semidefinite programming relaxation and apply the random hyperplane technique introduced by Goemans and Williamson for the MaxCut problem; this leads to an improved 1.2752-approximation.", :doc-id "Convex quadratic and semidefinite programming relaxations in scheduling. 2001  "}, 1013280 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1013280, :key "journals/mor/Solodov04", :title "On the Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Methods.", :abstract "An iteration of the sequential quadratically constrained quadratic programming method (SQCQP) consists of minimizing a quadratic approximation of the objective function subject to quadratic approximation of the constraints, followed by a line search in the obtained direction. Methods of this class are receiving attention due to the development of efficient interior point techniques for solving subproblems with this structure, via formulating them as second-order cone programs. Recently, Fukushima et al. (2003) proposed a SQCQP method for convex minimization with twice continuously differentiable data. Their method possesses global and locally quadratic convergence, and it is free of the Maratos effect. The feasibility of subproblems in their method is enforced by switching between the linear and quadratic approximations of the constraints. This strategy requires computing a strictly feasible point, as well as choosing some further parameters. We propose a SQCQP method where feasibility of subproblems is ensured by introducing a slack variable and, hence, is automatic. In addition, we do not assume convexity of the objective function or twice differentiability of the problem data. While our method has all the desirable convergence properties, it is easier to implement. Among other things, it does not require computing a strictly feasible point, which is a nontrivial task. In addition, its global convergence requires weaker assumptions.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 201619, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mikhail V. Solodov"}), :year 2004, :venue "Math. Oper. Res.", :ncit 24, :string "On the Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Methods.. An iteration of the sequential quadratically constrained quadratic programming method (SQCQP) consists of minimizing a quadratic approximation of the objective function subject to quadratic approximation of the constraints, followed by a line search in the obtained direction. Methods of this class are receiving attention due to the development of efficient interior point techniques for solving subproblems with this structure, via formulating them as second-order cone programs. Recently, Fukushima et al. (2003) proposed a SQCQP method for convex minimization with twice continuously differentiable data. Their method possesses global and locally quadratic convergence, and it is free of the Maratos effect. The feasibility of subproblems in their method is enforced by switching between the linear and quadratic approximations of the constraints. This strategy requires computing a strictly feasible point, as well as choosing some further parameters. We propose a SQCQP method where feasibility of subproblems is ensured by introducing a slack variable and, hence, is automatic. In addition, we do not assume convexity of the objective function or twice differentiability of the problem data. While our method has all the desirable convergence properties, it is easier to implement. Among other things, it does not require computing a strictly feasible point, which is a nontrivial task. In addition, its global convergence requires weaker assumptions.", :doc-id "On the Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Methods. 2004  "}, 3690304 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3690304, :key "journals/automatica/FellerJO13", :title "An improved algorithm for combinatorial multi-parametric quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14388928, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Christian Feller"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 667293, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Tor Arne Johansen"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 970588, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Sorin Olaru"}), :year 2013, :venue "Automatica", :ncit 0, :string "An improved algorithm for combinatorial multi-parametric quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "An improved algorithm for combinatorial multi-parametric quadratic programming. 2013  ,  ,  "}, 3631329 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3631329, :key "conf/cdc/DurrSE12", :title "A smooth vector field for quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14286168, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Hans-Bernd Durr"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14388912, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Erkin Saka"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 647187, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Christian Ebenbauer"}), :year 2012, :venue "CDC", :ncit 0, :string "A smooth vector field for quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "A smooth vector field for quadratic programming. 2012  ,  ,  "}, 934178 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 934178, :key "journals/ipl/Vavasis90", :title "Quadratic Programming is in NP.", :abstract "Quadratic programming is an important example of optimization with applications to engineering design, coombinatorical optimization, game theory, and economics. Garey and Johnson [1979] state that quadratic programming is NP-hard. In this report we show that it lies in NP, thereby proving that it is NP-complete.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 793748, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Stephen A. Vavasis"}), :year 1990, :venue "Inf. Process. Lett.", :ncit 64, :string "Quadratic Programming is in NP.. Quadratic programming is an important example of optimization with applications to engineering design, coombinatorical optimization, game theory, and economics. Garey and Johnson [1979] state that quadratic programming is NP-hard. In this report we show that it lies in NP, thereby proving that it is NP-complete.", :doc-id "Quadratic Programming is in NP. 1990  "}, 1321155 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1321155, :key "conf/isda/LiangBL08", :title "Sequential Quadratic Programming Based on IPM for Constrained Nonlinear Programming.", :abstract "The field of constrained nonlinear programming (NLP) has been principally challenging to various gradient based optimization techniques. The Sequential quadratic programming algorithm (SQP) that uses active set strategy in solving quadratic programming (QP) subproblems proves to be efficient in locating the points of local optima. However, its efficient determination of the optimal active set heavily relies on the initial guess of the starting point. This remains a serious drawback to both primal and dual active set approaches especially for NLPs with several inequality constraints. Thus, we propose a sequential quadratic programming algorithm (SQP/IPM) which uses an infeasible interior point method (IIPM) for the determination of descent directions. We propose using quadratic search algorithm for effective minimization of merit functions. Our test results reveal that SQP/IPM algorithm is efficient and promising.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1196303, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ximing Liang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1437248, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Hassan A. Bashir"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 629048, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shanchun Li"}), :year 2008, :venue "ISDA (1)", :ncit 0, :string "Sequential Quadratic Programming Based on IPM for Constrained Nonlinear Programming.. The field of constrained nonlinear programming (NLP) has been principally challenging to various gradient based optimization techniques. The Sequential quadratic programming algorithm (SQP) that uses active set strategy in solving quadratic programming (QP) subproblems proves to be efficient in locating the points of local optima. However, its efficient determination of the optimal active set heavily relies on the initial guess of the starting point. This remains a serious drawback to both primal and dual active set approaches especially for NLPs with several inequality constraints. Thus, we propose a sequential quadratic programming algorithm (SQP/IPM) which uses an infeasible interior point method (IIPM) for the determination of descent directions. We propose using quadratic search algorithm for effective minimization of merit functions. Our test results reveal that SQP/IPM algorithm is efficient and promising.", :doc-id "Sequential Quadratic Programming Based on IPM for Constrained Nonlinear Programming. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 3458339 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3458339, :key "journals/coap/JungOT12", :title "Adaptive constraint reduction for convex quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14304884, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jin Hyuk Jung"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 468805, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dianne P. O'Leary"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1223243, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "André L. Tits"}), :year 2012, :venue "Comp. Opt. and Appl.", :ncit 8, :string "Adaptive constraint reduction for convex quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "Adaptive constraint reduction for convex quadratic programming. 2012  ,  ,  "}, 1013956 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1013956, :key "journals/mp/Linderoth05", :title "A simplicial branch-and-bound algorithm for solving quadratically constrained quadratic programs.", :abstract "We propose a branch-and-bound algorithm for solving nonconvex quadratically-constrained quadratic programs. The algorithm is novel in that branching is done by partitioning the feasible region into the Cartesian product of two-dimensional triangles and rectangles. Explicit formulae for the convex and concave envelopes of bilinear functions over triangles and rectangles are derived and shown to be second-order cone representable. The usefulness of these new relaxations is demonstrated both theoretically and computationally.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1047055, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jeff Linderoth"}), :year 2005, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 34, :string "A simplicial branch-and-bound algorithm for solving quadratically constrained quadratic programs.. We propose a branch-and-bound algorithm for solving nonconvex quadratically-constrained quadratic programs. The algorithm is novel in that branching is done by partitioning the feasible region into the Cartesian product of two-dimensional triangles and rectangles. Explicit formulae for the convex and concave envelopes of bilinear functions over triangles and rectangles are derived and shown to be second-order cone representable. The usefulness of these new relaxations is demonstrated both theoretically and computationally.", :doc-id "A simplicial branch-and-bound algorithm for solving quadratically constrained quadratic programs. 2005  "}, 2932068 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2932068, :key "journals/eor/SunZ10", :title "A modified alternating direction method for convex quadratically constrained quadratic semidefinite programs.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 361201, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jie Sun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1400249, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Su Zhang"}), :year 2010, :venue "European Journal of Operational Research", :ncit 29, :string "A modified alternating direction method for convex quadratically constrained quadratic semidefinite programs.. ", :doc-id "A modified alternating direction method for convex quadratically constrained quadratic semidefinite programs. 2010  ,  "}, 1013348 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1013348, :key "journals/mp/Ben-TalT96", :title "Hidden convexity in some nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1255603, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Aharon Ben-Tal"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1515505, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Marc Teboulle"}), :year 1996, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 76, :string "Hidden convexity in some nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "Hidden convexity in some nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming. 1996  ,  "}, 814884 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 814884, :key "journals/cor/BestH08", :title "Quadratic programming with transaction costs.", :abstract "We consider the problem of maximizing the mean-variance utility function of n assets. Associated with a change in an asset's holdings from its current or target value is a transaction cost. These must be accounted for in practical problems. A straightforward way of doing so results in a 3n-dimensional optimization problem with 3n additional constraints. This higher dimensional problem is computationally expensive to solve. We present an algorithm for solving the 3n-dimensional problem by modifying an active set quadratic programming (QP) algorithm to solve the 3n-dimensional problem as an n-dimensional problem accounting for the transaction costs implicitly rather than explicitly. The method is based on deriving the optimality conditions for the higher dimensional problem solely in terms of lower dimensional quantities and requires substantially less computational effort than any active set QP algorithm applied directly on a 3n-dimensional problem.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1339305, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Michael J. Best"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1401747, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jaroslava Hlouskova"}), :year 2008, :venue "Computers & OR", :ncit 4, :string "Quadratic programming with transaction costs.. We consider the problem of maximizing the mean-variance utility function of n assets. Associated with a change in an asset's holdings from its current or target value is a transaction cost. These must be accounted for in practical problems. A straightforward way of doing so results in a 3n-dimensional optimization problem with 3n additional constraints. This higher dimensional problem is computationally expensive to solve. We present an algorithm for solving the 3n-dimensional problem by modifying an active set quadratic programming (QP) algorithm to solve the 3n-dimensional problem as an n-dimensional problem accounting for the transaction costs implicitly rather than explicitly. The method is based on deriving the optimality conditions for the higher dimensional problem solely in terms of lower dimensional quantities and requires substantially less computational effort than any active set QP algorithm applied directly on a 3n-dimensional problem.", :doc-id "Quadratic programming with transaction costs. 2008  ,  "}, 3701732 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3701732, :key "journals/coap/BaiMP13", :title "On convex quadratic programs with linear complementarity constraints.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14274731, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Lijie Bai"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 243480, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "John E. Mitchell"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 911106, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jong-Shi Pang"}), :year 2013, :venue "Comp. Opt. and Appl.", :ncit 0, :string "On convex quadratic programs with linear complementarity constraints.. ", :doc-id "On convex quadratic programs with linear complementarity constraints. 2013  ,  ,  "}, 1121349 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1121349, :key "journals/toms/GertzW03", :title "Object-oriented software for quadratic programming.", :abstract "The object-oriented software package OOQP for solving convex quadratic programming problems (QP) is described. The primal-dual interior point algorithms supplied by OOQP are implemented in a way that is largely independent of the problem structure. Users may exploit problem structure by supplying linear algebra, problem data, and variable classes that are customized to their particular applications. The OOQP distribution contains default implementations that solve several important QP problem types, including general sparse and dense QPs, bound-constrained QPs, and QPs arising from support vector machines and Huber regression. The implementations supplied with the OOQP distribution are based on such well known linear algebra packages as MA27/57, LAPACK, and PETSc. OOQP demonstrates the usefulness of object-oriented design in optimization software development, and establishes standards that can be followed in the design of software packages for other classes of optimization problems. A number of the classes in OOQP may also be reusable directly in other codes.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 240957, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "E. Michael Gertz"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 106154, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Stephen J. Wright"}), :year 2003, :venue "ACM Trans. Math. Softw.", :ncit 164, :string "Object-oriented software for quadratic programming.. The object-oriented software package OOQP for solving convex quadratic programming problems (QP) is described. The primal-dual interior point algorithms supplied by OOQP are implemented in a way that is largely independent of the problem structure. Users may exploit problem structure by supplying linear algebra, problem data, and variable classes that are customized to their particular applications. The OOQP distribution contains default implementations that solve several important QP problem types, including general sparse and dense QPs, bound-constrained QPs, and QPs arising from support vector machines and Huber regression. The implementations supplied with the OOQP distribution are based on such well known linear algebra packages as MA27/57, LAPACK, and PETSc. OOQP demonstrates the usefulness of object-oriented design in optimization software development, and establishes standards that can be followed in the design of software packages for other classes of optimization problems. A number of the classes in OOQP may also be reusable directly in other codes.", :doc-id "Object-oriented software for quadratic programming. 2003  ,  "}, 3390693 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3390693, :key "journals/fss/KheirfamV12", :title "Strict sensitivity analysis in fuzzy quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14265141, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Behrouz Kheirfam"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 190623, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "José L. Verdegay"}), :year 2012, :venue "Fuzzy Sets and Systems", :ncit 1, :string "Strict sensitivity analysis in fuzzy quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "Strict sensitivity analysis in fuzzy quadratic programming. 2012  ,  "}, 737061 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 737061, :key "journals/4or/Plateau08", :title "Quadratic convex reformulations for quadratic 0-1 programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 495741, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Marie-Christine Plateau"}), :year 2008, :venue "4OR", :ncit 1, :string "Quadratic convex reformulations for quadratic 0-1 programming.. ", :doc-id "Quadratic convex reformulations for quadratic 0-1 programming. 2008  "}, 2891653 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2891653, :key "journals/siamjo/BurerL09", :title "On Nonconvex Quadratic Programming with Box Constraints.", :abstract "Nonconvex quadratic programming with box constraints is a fundamental $\\mathcal{NP}$-hard global optimization problem. Recently, some authors have studied a certain family of convex sets associated with this problem. We prove several fundamental results concerned with these convex sets: we determine their dimension, characterize their extreme points and vertices, show their invariance under certain affine transformations, and show that various linear inequalities induce facets. We also show that the sets are closely related to the Boolean quadric polytope, a fundamental polytope in the field of polyhedral combinatorics. Finally, we give a classification of valid inequalities and show that this yields a finite recursive procedure to check the validity of any proposed inequality.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1037897, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Samuel Burer"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 213390, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Adam N. Letchford"}), :year 2009, :venue "SIAM Journal on Optimization", :ncit 20, :string "On Nonconvex Quadratic Programming with Box Constraints.. Nonconvex quadratic programming with box constraints is a fundamental $\\mathcal{NP}$-hard global optimization problem. Recently, some authors have studied a certain family of convex sets associated with this problem. We prove several fundamental results concerned with these convex sets: we determine their dimension, characterize their extreme points and vertices, show their invariance under certain affine transformations, and show that various linear inequalities induce facets. We also show that the sets are closely related to the Boolean quadric polytope, a fundamental polytope in the field of polyhedral combinatorics. Finally, we give a classification of valid inequalities and show that this yields a finite recursive procedure to check the validity of any proposed inequality.", :doc-id "On Nonconvex Quadratic Programming with Box Constraints. 2009  ,  "}, 1340678 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1340678, :key "journals/mp/KlerkS10", :title "Exploiting group symmetry in semidefinite programming relaxations of the quadratic assignment problem.", :abstract "We consider semidefinite programming relaxations of the quadratic assignment problem, and show how to exploit group symmetry in the problem data. Thus we are able to compute the best known lower bounds for several instances of quadratic assignment problems from the problem library: (Burkard et al. in J Global Optim 10:291&#x2013;403, 1997).", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 559660, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Etienne de Klerk"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 26655, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Renata Sotirov"}), :year 2010, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 51, :string "Exploiting group symmetry in semidefinite programming relaxations of the quadratic assignment problem.. We consider semidefinite programming relaxations of the quadratic assignment problem, and show how to exploit group symmetry in the problem data. Thus we are able to compute the best known lower bounds for several instances of quadratic assignment problems from the problem library: (Burkard et al. in J Global Optim 10:291&#x2013;403, 1997).", :doc-id "Exploiting group symmetry in semidefinite programming relaxations of the quadratic assignment problem. 2010  ,  "}, 861574 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 861574, :key "journals/eccc/ECCC-TR05-058", :title "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs", :abstract "This paper studies the computational complexity of the following type of quadratic programs: given an arbitrary matrix whose diagonal elements are zero, find \\chi \\varepsilon {-1, 1}^n that maximizes \\chi ^{\\rm T} Mx this problem recently attracted attention due to its application in various clustering settings, as well as an intriguing connection to the famous Grothendieck inequality. It is approximable to within a factor of O(log n), and known to be NP-hard to approximate within any factor better than 13/110 - \\varepsilon for all \\varepsilon > O. We show showthat it is quasi-NP-hard to approximate to a factor better than O(Log^\\gamman) for some \\gamma > 0.The integrality gap of the natural semide?nite relaxation for this problem is known as the Grothendieck constant the complete graph, and known to be \\theta (\\log n). The proof this fact was nonconstructive, and did not yield an explicit problem instance where this integrality gap is achieved. Our techniques yield an explicit instance for which the integrality gap is \\Omega (\\frac{{\\log n}}{{\\log \\log n}}), essentially answering one of the open problems of Alon et al. [AMMN].", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 551434, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Sanjeev Arora"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 951245, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Eli Berger"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1185518, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Elad Hazan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 289609, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Guy Kindler"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1280124, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Muli Safra"}), :year 2005, :venue "Electronic Colloquium on Computational Complexity (ECCC)", :ncit 39, :string "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs. This paper studies the computational complexity of the following type of quadratic programs: given an arbitrary matrix whose diagonal elements are zero, find \\chi \\varepsilon {-1, 1}^n that maximizes \\chi ^{\\rm T} Mx this problem recently attracted attention due to its application in various clustering settings, as well as an intriguing connection to the famous Grothendieck inequality. It is approximable to within a factor of O(log n), and known to be NP-hard to approximate within any factor better than 13/110 - \\varepsilon for all \\varepsilon > O. We show showthat it is quasi-NP-hard to approximate to a factor better than O(Log^\\gamman) for some \\gamma > 0.The integrality gap of the natural semide?nite relaxation for this problem is known as the Grothendieck constant the complete graph, and known to be \\theta (\\log n). The proof this fact was nonconstructive, and did not yield an explicit problem instance where this integrality gap is achieved. Our techniques yield an explicit instance for which the integrality gap is \\Omega (\\frac{{\\log n}}{{\\log \\log n}}), essentially answering one of the open problems of Alon et al. [AMMN].", :doc-id "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs 2005  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3160774 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3160774, :key "journals/mp/BaoST11", :title "Semidefinite relaxations for quadratically constrained quadratic programming: A review and comparisons.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 820325, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaowei Bao"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 758242, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nikolaos V. Sahinidis"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 67375, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mohit Tawarmalani"}), :year 2011, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 6, :string "Semidefinite relaxations for quadratically constrained quadratic programming: A review and comparisons.. ", :doc-id "Semidefinite relaxations for quadratically constrained quadratic programming: A review and comparisons. 2011  ,  ,  "}, 775974 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 775974, :key "journals/cacm/Shrager72", :title "Quadratic Programming for Nonlinear Regression.", :abstract "A quadratic programming algorithm is described for use with the magnified diagonal method of nonlinear regression with linear constraints. The regression method is published in JACM, July 1970.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 582417, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Richard I. Shrager"}), :year 1972, :venue "Commun. ACM", :ncit 0, :string "Quadratic Programming for Nonlinear Regression.. A quadratic programming algorithm is described for use with the magnified diagonal method of nonlinear regression with linear constraints. The regression method is published in JACM, July 1970.", :doc-id "Quadratic Programming for Nonlinear Regression. 1972  "}, 3730855 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3730855, :key "journals/ijon/YuanZGH13", :title "Low-rank quadratic semidefinite programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14312880, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ganzhao Yuan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1346004, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhenjie Zhang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1377765, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Bernard Ghanem"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1478969, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhifeng Hao"}), :year 2013, :venue "Neurocomputing", :ncit 0, :string "Low-rank quadratic semidefinite programming.. ", :doc-id "Low-rank quadratic semidefinite programming. 2013  ,  ,  ,  "}, 341543 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 341543, :key "conf/icpads/SernaX97", :title "The Parallel Approximability of a Subclass of Quadratic Programming.", :abstract "In this paper we deal with the parallel approximability of a special class of Quadratic Programming (QP), called Smooth Positive Quadratic Programming. This subclass of QP is obtained by imposing restrictions on the coefficients of the QP instance. The Smoothness condition restricts the magnitudes of the coefficients while the positiveness requires that all the coefficients be non-negative. Interestingly, even with these restrictions several combinatorial problems can be modeled by Smooth QP.We show NC Approximation Schemes for the instances of Smooth Positive QP. This is done by reducing the instance of QP to an instance of Positive Linear Programming, finding in NC an approximate fractional solution to the obtained program, and then rounding the fractional solution to an integer approximate solution for the original problem. Then we show how to extend the result for positive instances of bounded degree to Smooth Integer Programming problems. Finally, we formulate several important combinatorial problems as Positive Quadratic Programs (or Positive Integer Programs) in packing/covering form and show that the techniques presented can be used to obtain NC Approximation Schemes for \"dense\" instances of such problems.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 373038, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Maria J. Serna"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 678017, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Fatos Xhafa"}), :year 1997, :venue "ICPADS", :ncit 3, :string "The Parallel Approximability of a Subclass of Quadratic Programming.. In this paper we deal with the parallel approximability of a special class of Quadratic Programming (QP), called Smooth Positive Quadratic Programming. This subclass of QP is obtained by imposing restrictions on the coefficients of the QP instance. The Smoothness condition restricts the magnitudes of the coefficients while the positiveness requires that all the coefficients be non-negative. Interestingly, even with these restrictions several combinatorial problems can be modeled by Smooth QP.We show NC Approximation Schemes for the instances of Smooth Positive QP. This is done by reducing the instance of QP to an instance of Positive Linear Programming, finding in NC an approximate fractional solution to the obtained program, and then rounding the fractional solution to an integer approximate solution for the original problem. Then we show how to extend the result for positive instances of bounded degree to Smooth Integer Programming problems. Finally, we formulate several important combinatorial problems as Positive Quadratic Programs (or Positive Integer Programs) in packing/covering form and show that the techniques presented can be used to obtain NC Approximation Schemes for \"dense\" instances of such problems.", :doc-id "The Parallel Approximability of a Subclass of Quadratic Programming. 1997  ,  "}, 3394183 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3394183, :key "journals/mp/HuMP12", :title "An LPCC approach to nonconvex quadratic programs.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 410998, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jing Hu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 243480, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "John E. Mitchell"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 911106, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jong-Shi Pang"}), :year 2012, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 18, :string "An LPCC approach to nonconvex quadratic programs.. ", :doc-id "An LPCC approach to nonconvex quadratic programs. 2012  ,  ,  "}, 3287783 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3287783, :key "conf/icip/BrandC11", :title "Parallel quadratic programming for image processing.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 646501, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Matthew Brand"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 670630, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Donghui Chen"}), :year 2011, :venue "ICIP", :ncit 0, :string "Parallel quadratic programming for image processing.. ", :doc-id "Parallel quadratic programming for image processing. 2011  ,  "}, 1322791 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1322791, :key "conf/fskd/Li09c", :title "Algorithm for Interval Quadratic Programming with Equality Constraints.", :abstract "Recently, Li and Tian described an interesting numerical method of interval quadratic programming with inequality constraints, where all coefficients in the objective function and constraints are interval numbers. In this paper, we generalize Li and Tian's method to interval quadratic programming with equality constraint, which is more difficult to handle. A practical algorithm is established via an effective transformation of interval programming to conventional mathematic programming. The ACM Portal is published by the Association for Computing Machinery. Copyright © 2010 ACM, Inc. Terms of Usage Privacy Policy Code of Ethics Contact Us Useful downloads: Adobe Acrobat QuickTime Windows Media Player Real Player", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1073905, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Wei Li"}), :year 2009, :venue "FSKD (6)", :ncit 2, :string "Algorithm for Interval Quadratic Programming with Equality Constraints.. Recently, Li and Tian described an interesting numerical method of interval quadratic programming with inequality constraints, where all coefficients in the objective function and constraints are interval numbers. In this paper, we generalize Li and Tian's method to interval quadratic programming with equality constraint, which is more difficult to handle. A practical algorithm is established via an effective transformation of interval programming to conventional mathematic programming. The ACM Portal is published by the Association for Computing Machinery. Copyright © 2010 ACM, Inc. Terms of Usage Privacy Policy Code of Ethics Contact Us Useful downloads: Adobe Acrobat QuickTime Windows Media Player Real Player", :doc-id "Algorithm for Interval Quadratic Programming with Equality Constraints. 2009  "}, 1340649 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1340649, :key "journals/mp/Burer09", :title "On the copositive representation of binary and continuous nonconvex quadratic programs.", :abstract "In this paper, we model any nonconvex quadratic program having a mix of binary and continuous variables as a linear program over the dual of the cone of copositive matrices. This result can be viewed as an extension of earlier separate results, which have established the copositive representation of a small collection of NP-hard problems. A simplification, which reduces the dimension of the linear conic program, and an extension to complementarity constraints are established, and computational issues are discussed.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1037897, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Samuel Burer"}), :year 2009, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 85, :string "On the copositive representation of binary and continuous nonconvex quadratic programs.. In this paper, we model any nonconvex quadratic program having a mix of binary and continuous variables as a linear program over the dual of the cone of copositive matrices. This result can be viewed as an extension of earlier separate results, which have established the copositive representation of a small collection of NP-hard problems. A simplification, which reduces the dimension of the linear conic program, and an extension to complementarity constraints are established, and computational issues are discussed.", :doc-id "On the copositive representation of binary and continuous nonconvex quadratic programs. 2009  "}, 3551242 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3551242, :key "journals/mpc/BomzeJR11", :title "Quadratic factorization heuristics for copositive programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 543259, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Immanuel M. Bomze"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1258736, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Florian Jarre"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1207721, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Franz Rendl"}), :year 2011, :venue "Math. Program. Comput.", :ncit 7, :string "Quadratic factorization heuristics for copositive programming.. ", :doc-id "Quadratic factorization heuristics for copositive programming. 2011  ,  ,  "}, 3472010 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3472010, :key "journals/corr/abs-1206-1633", :title "Linear Programming Relaxations of Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programs", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 55677, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Andrea Qualizza"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 766598, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Pietro Belotti"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1290631, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "François Margot"}), :year 2012, :venue "CoRR", :ncit 0, :string "Linear Programming Relaxations of Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programs. ", :doc-id "Linear Programming Relaxations of Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programs 2012  ,  ,  "}, 1013738 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1013738, :key "journals/mp/GouldT04", :title "Preprocessing for quadratic programming.", :abstract "Techniques for the preprocessing of (not-necessarily convex) quadratic programs are discussed. Most of the procedures extend known ones from the linear to quadratic cases, but a few new preprocessing techniques are introduced. The implementation aspects are also discussed. Numerical results are finally presented to indicate the potential of the resulting code, both for linear and quadratic problems. The impact of insisting that bounds of the variables in the reduced problem be as tight as possible rather than allowing some slack in these bounds is also shown to be numerically significant.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1371079, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Nick I. M. Gould"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1256407, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Philippe L. Toint"}), :year 2004, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 27, :string "Preprocessing for quadratic programming.. Techniques for the preprocessing of (not-necessarily convex) quadratic programs are discussed. Most of the procedures extend known ones from the linear to quadratic cases, but a few new preprocessing techniques are introduced. The implementation aspects are also discussed. Numerical results are finally presented to indicate the potential of the resulting code, both for linear and quadratic problems. The impact of insisting that bounds of the variables in the reduced problem be as tight as possible rather than allowing some slack in these bounds is also shown to be numerically significant.", :doc-id "Preprocessing for quadratic programming. 2004  ,  "}, 3715211 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3715211, :key "journals/apjor/JiZS13", :title "An Improved Convex 0-1 quadratic Program Reformulation for Chance-Constrained quadratic Knapsack Problems.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14423605, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shuhui Ji"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1483646, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaojin Zheng"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1085608, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaoling Sun"}), :year 2013, :venue "APJOR", :ncit 0, :string "An Improved Convex 0-1 quadratic Program Reformulation for Chance-Constrained quadratic Knapsack Problems.. ", :doc-id "An Improved Convex 0-1 quadratic Program Reformulation for Chance-Constrained quadratic Knapsack Problems. 2013  ,  ,  "}, 3621675 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3621675, :key "journals/jota/Auslender13", :title "An Extended Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Nonlinear, Semidefinite, and Second-Order Cone Programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1523242, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Alfred Auslender"}), :year 2013, :venue "J. Optimization Theory and Applications", :ncit 0, :string "An Extended Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Nonlinear, Semidefinite, and Second-Order Cone Programming.. ", :doc-id "An Extended Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Nonlinear, Semidefinite, and Second-Order Cone Programming. 2013  "}, 1023373 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1023373, :key "journals/neco/WuZ05", :title "SVM Soft Margin Classifiers: Linear Programming versus Quadratic Programming.", :abstract "Support vector machine (SVM) soft margin classifiers are important learning algorithms for classification problems. They can be stated as convex optimization problems and are suitable for a large data setting. Linear programming SVM classifiers are especially efficient for very large size samples. But little is known about their convergence, compared with the well-understood quadratic programming SVM classifier. In this article, we point out the difficulty and provide an error analysis. Our analysis shows that the convergence behavior of the linear programming SVM is almost the same as that of the quadratic programming SVM. This is implemented by setting a stepping-stone between the linear programming SVM and the classical 1-norm soft margin classifier. An upper bound for the misclassification error is presented for general probability distributions. Explicit learning rates are derived for deterministic and weakly separable distributions, and for distributions satisfying some Tsybakov noise condition.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 341901, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Qiang Wu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 804502, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ding-Xuan Zhou"}), :year 2005, :venue "Neural Computation", :ncit 81, :string "SVM Soft Margin Classifiers: Linear Programming versus Quadratic Programming.. Support vector machine (SVM) soft margin classifiers are important learning algorithms for classification problems. They can be stated as convex optimization problems and are suitable for a large data setting. Linear programming SVM classifiers are especially efficient for very large size samples. But little is known about their convergence, compared with the well-understood quadratic programming SVM classifier. In this article, we point out the difficulty and provide an error analysis. Our analysis shows that the convergence behavior of the linear programming SVM is almost the same as that of the quadratic programming SVM. This is implemented by setting a stepping-stone between the linear programming SVM and the classical 1-norm soft margin classifier. An upper bound for the misclassification error is presented for general probability distributions. Explicit learning rates are derived for deterministic and weakly separable distributions, and for distributions satisfying some Tsybakov noise condition.", :doc-id "SVM Soft Margin Classifiers: Linear Programming versus Quadratic Programming. 2005  ,  "}, 2866414 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2866414, :key "journals/mp/GoldfarbI03", :title "Robust convex quadratically constrained programs.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 561606, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Donald Goldfarb"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1426951, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Garud Iyengar"}), :year 2003, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 90, :string "Robust convex quadratically constrained programs.. ", :doc-id "Robust convex quadratically constrained programs. 2003  ,  "}, 1023854 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1023854, :key "journals/neco/ShaLSL07", :title "Multiplicative Updates for Nonnegative Quadratic Programming.", :abstract "Many problems in neural computation and statistical learning involve optimizations with nonnegativity constraints. In this article, we study convex problems in quadratic programming where the optimization is confined to an axis-aligned region in the nonnegative orthant. For these problems, we derive multiplicative updates that improve the value of the objective function at each iteration and converge monotonically to the global minimum. The updates have a simple closed form and do not involve any heuristics or free parameters that must be tuned to ensure convergence. Despite their simplicity, they differ strikingly in form from other multiplicative updates used in machine learning. We provide complete proofs of convergence for these updates and describe their application to problems in signal processing and pattern recognition.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 992646, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Fei Sha"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 577131, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yuanqing Lin"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 654708, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Lawrence K. Saul"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 995863, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Daniel D. Lee"}), :year 2007, :venue "Neural Computation", :ncit 66, :string "Multiplicative Updates for Nonnegative Quadratic Programming.. Many problems in neural computation and statistical learning involve optimizations with nonnegativity constraints. In this article, we study convex problems in quadratic programming where the optimization is confined to an axis-aligned region in the nonnegative orthant. For these problems, we derive multiplicative updates that improve the value of the objective function at each iteration and converge monotonically to the global minimum. The updates have a simple closed form and do not involve any heuristics or free parameters that must be tuned to ensure convergence. Despite their simplicity, they differ strikingly in form from other multiplicative updates used in machine learning. We provide complete proofs of convergence for these updates and describe their application to problems in signal processing and pattern recognition.", :doc-id "Multiplicative Updates for Nonnegative Quadratic Programming. 2007  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3366063 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3366063, :key "journals/eor/ZhengSLC12", :title "Lagrangian decomposition and mixed-integer quadratic programming reformulations for probabilistically constrained quadratic programs.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1483646, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaojin Zheng"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1085608, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaoling Sun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 118392, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Duan Li"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14259046, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xueting Cui"}), :year 2012, :venue "European Journal of Operational Research", :ncit 6, :string "Lagrangian decomposition and mixed-integer quadratic programming reformulations for probabilistically constrained quadratic programs.. ", :doc-id "Lagrangian decomposition and mixed-integer quadratic programming reformulations for probabilistically constrained quadratic programs. 2012  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3363311 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3363311, :key "journals/jgo/SunLLG12", :title "On duality gap in binary quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1221963, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "X. L. Sun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 103519, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "C. L. Liu"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1023363, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "D. Li"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 592020, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "J. J. Gao"}), :year 2012, :venue "J. Global Optimization", :ncit 2, :string "On duality gap in binary quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "On duality gap in binary quadratic programming. 2012  ,  ,  ,  "}, 1199887 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1199887, :key "reference/opt/Tits09", :title "Feasible Sequential Quadratic Programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1180881, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "André L. Tits"}), :year 2009, :venue "Encyclopedia of Optimization", :ncit 0, :string "Feasible Sequential Quadratic Programming.. ", :doc-id "Feasible Sequential Quadratic Programming. 2009  "}, 473584 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 473584, :key "conf/kdd/YeJC07", :title "Learning the kernel matrix in discriminant analysis via quadratically constrained quadratic programming.", :abstract "The kernel function plays a central role in kernel methods. In this paper, we consider the automated learning of the kernel matrix over a convex combination of pre-specified kernel matrices in Regularized Kernel Discriminant Analysis (RKDA), which performs lineardiscriminant analysis in the feature space via the kernel trick. Previous studies have shown that this kernel learning problem can be formulated as a semidefinite program (SDP), which is however computationally expensive, even with the recent advances in interior point methods. Based on the equivalence relationship between RKDA and least square problems in the binary-class case, we propose a Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming (QCQP) formulation for the kernel learning problem, which can be solved more efficiently than SDP. While most existing work on kernel learning deal with binary-class problems only, we show that our QCQP formulation can be extended naturally to the multi-class case. Experimental results on both binary-class and multi-class benchmarkdata sets show the efficacy of the proposed QCQP formulations.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1406190, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jieping Ye"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1404867, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shuiwang Ji"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 26971, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jianhui Chen"}), :year 2007, :venue "KDD", :ncit 17, :string "Learning the kernel matrix in discriminant analysis via quadratically constrained quadratic programming.. The kernel function plays a central role in kernel methods. In this paper, we consider the automated learning of the kernel matrix over a convex combination of pre-specified kernel matrices in Regularized Kernel Discriminant Analysis (RKDA), which performs lineardiscriminant analysis in the feature space via the kernel trick. Previous studies have shown that this kernel learning problem can be formulated as a semidefinite program (SDP), which is however computationally expensive, even with the recent advances in interior point methods. Based on the equivalence relationship between RKDA and least square problems in the binary-class case, we propose a Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming (QCQP) formulation for the kernel learning problem, which can be solved more efficiently than SDP. While most existing work on kernel learning deal with binary-class problems only, we show that our QCQP formulation can be extended naturally to the multi-class case. Experimental results on both binary-class and multi-class benchmarkdata sets show the efficacy of the proposed QCQP formulations.", :doc-id "Learning the kernel matrix in discriminant analysis via quadratically constrained quadratic programming. 2007  ,  ,  "}, 272912 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 272912, :key "conf/icann/SignorettoPS08", :title "Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming for Subspace Selection in Kernel Regression Estimation.", :abstract "In this contribution we consider the problem of regression estimation. We elaborate on a framework based on functional analysis giving rise to structured models in the context of reproducing kernel Hilbert spaces. In this setting the task of input selection is converted into the task of selecting functional components depending on one (or more) inputs. In turn the process of learning with embedded selection of such components can be formalized as a convex-concave problem. This results in a practical algorithm that can be implemented as a quadratically constrained quadratic programming (QCQP) optimization problem. We further investigate the mechanism of selection for the class of linear functions, establishing a relationship with LASSO.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 88936, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Marco Signoretto"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1231600, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Kristiaan Pelckmans"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 200686, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Johan A. K. Suykens"}), :year 2008, :venue "ICANN (1)", :ncit 10, :string "Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming for Subspace Selection in Kernel Regression Estimation.. In this contribution we consider the problem of regression estimation. We elaborate on a framework based on functional analysis giving rise to structured models in the context of reproducing kernel Hilbert spaces. In this setting the task of input selection is converted into the task of selecting functional components depending on one (or more) inputs. In turn the process of learning with embedded selection of such components can be formalized as a convex-concave problem. This results in a practical algorithm that can be implemented as a quadratically constrained quadratic programming (QCQP) optimization problem. We further investigate the mechanism of selection for the class of linear functions, establishing a relationship with LASSO.", :doc-id "Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming for Subspace Selection in Kernel Regression Estimation. 2008  ,  ,  "}, 2892049 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2892049, :key "journals/siamjo/Anitescu02", :title "A Superlinearly Convergent Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Degenerate Nonlinear Programming.", :abstract "We present an algorithm that achieves superlinear convergence for nonlinear programs satisfying the Mangasarian--Fromovitz constraint qualification and the quadratic growth condition. This convergence result is obtained despite the potential lack of a locally convex augmented Lagrangian. The algorithm solves a succession of subproblems that have quadratic objectives and quadratic constraints, both possibly nonconvex. By the use of a trust-region constraint we guarantee that any stationary point of the subproblem induces superlinear convergence, which avoids the problem of computing a global minimum. We compare this algorithm with sequential quadratic programming algorithms on several degenerate nonlinear programs.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 956666, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mihai Anitescu"}), :year 2002, :venue "SIAM Journal on Optimization", :ncit 29, :string "A Superlinearly Convergent Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Degenerate Nonlinear Programming.. We present an algorithm that achieves superlinear convergence for nonlinear programs satisfying the Mangasarian--Fromovitz constraint qualification and the quadratic growth condition. This convergence result is obtained despite the potential lack of a locally convex augmented Lagrangian. The algorithm solves a succession of subproblems that have quadratic objectives and quadratic constraints, both possibly nonconvex. By the use of a trust-region constraint we guarantee that any stationary point of the subproblem induces superlinear convergence, which avoids the problem of computing a global minimum. We compare this algorithm with sequential quadratic programming algorithms on several degenerate nonlinear programs.", :doc-id "A Superlinearly Convergent Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Algorithm for Degenerate Nonlinear Programming. 2002  "}, 2870961 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2870961, :key "journals/toms/Pardalos91", :title "Construction of test problems in quadratic bivalent programming.", :abstract "A method of constructing test problems for constrained bivalent quadratic programming is presented. For any feasible integer point for a given domain, the method generates quadratic functions whose minimum over the given domain occurs at the selected point. Certain properties of unconstrained quadratic zero-one programs that determine the difficulty of the test problems are also discussed. In addition, a standardized random test problem generator for unconstrained quadratic zero-one programming is given.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 218701, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Panos M. Pardalos"}), :year 1991, :venue "ACM Trans. Math. Softw.", :ncit 50, :string "Construction of test problems in quadratic bivalent programming.. A method of constructing test problems for constrained bivalent quadratic programming is presented. For any feasible integer point for a given domain, the method generates quadratic functions whose minimum over the given domain occurs at the selected point. Certain properties of unconstrained quadratic zero-one programs that determine the difficulty of the test problems are also discussed. In addition, a standardized random test problem generator for unconstrained quadratic zero-one programming is given.", :doc-id "Construction of test problems in quadratic bivalent programming. 1991  "}, 2892114 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2892114, :key "journals/siamjo/FukushimaLT03", :title "A Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Method for Differentiable Convex Minimization.", :abstract "This paper presents a sequential quadratically constrained quadratic programming (SQCQP) method for solving smooth convex programs. The SQCQP method solves at each iteration a subproblem that involves convex quadratic inequality constraints as well as a convex quadratic objective function. Such a quadratically constrained quadratic programming problem can be formulated as a second-order cone program, which can be solved efficiently by using interior point methods. We consider the following three fundamental issues on the SQCQP method: the feasibility of subproblems, the global convergence, and the quadratic rate of convergence. In particular, we show that the Maratos effect is avoided without any modification to the search direction, even though we use an ordinary $\\ell_1$ exact penalty function as the line search merit function.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 546401, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Masao Fukushima"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 846463, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhi-Quan Luo"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1360055, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Paul Tseng"}), :year 2003, :venue "SIAM Journal on Optimization", :ncit 34, :string "A Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Method for Differentiable Convex Minimization.. This paper presents a sequential quadratically constrained quadratic programming (SQCQP) method for solving smooth convex programs. The SQCQP method solves at each iteration a subproblem that involves convex quadratic inequality constraints as well as a convex quadratic objective function. Such a quadratically constrained quadratic programming problem can be formulated as a second-order cone program, which can be solved efficiently by using interior point methods. We consider the following three fundamental issues on the SQCQP method: the feasibility of subproblems, the global convergence, and the quadratic rate of convergence. In particular, we show that the Maratos effect is avoided without any modification to the search direction, even though we use an ordinary $\\ell_1$ exact penalty function as the line search merit function.", :doc-id "A Sequential Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming Method for Differentiable Convex Minimization. 2003  ,  ,  "}, 209939 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 209939, :key "conf/focs/AroraBKSH05", :title "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs.", :abstract "This paper studies the computational complexity of the following type of quadratic programs: given an arbitrary matrix whose diagonal elements are zero, find \\chi \\varepsilon {-1, 1}^n that maximizes \\chi ^{\\rm T} Mx this problem recently attracted attention due to its application in various clustering settings, as well as an intriguing connection to the famous Grothendieck inequality. It is approximable to within a factor of O(log n), and known to be NP-hard to approximate within any factor better than 13/110 - \\varepsilon for all \\varepsilon > O. We show showthat it is quasi-NP-hard to approximate to a factor better than O(Log^\\gamman) for some \\gamma > 0.The integrality gap of the natural semide?nite relaxation for this problem is known as the Grothendieck constant the complete graph, and known to be \\theta (\\log n). The proof this fact was nonconstructive, and did not yield an explicit problem instance where this integrality gap is achieved. Our techniques yield an explicit instance for which the integrality gap is \\Omega (\\frac{{\\log n}}{{\\log \\log n}}), essentially answering one of the open problems of Alon et al. [AMMN].", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 551434, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Sanjeev Arora"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 951245, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Eli Berger"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1185518, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Elad Hazan"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 289609, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Guy Kindler"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1280124, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Muli Safra"}), :year 2005, :venue "FOCS", :ncit 34, :string "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs.. This paper studies the computational complexity of the following type of quadratic programs: given an arbitrary matrix whose diagonal elements are zero, find \\chi \\varepsilon {-1, 1}^n that maximizes \\chi ^{\\rm T} Mx this problem recently attracted attention due to its application in various clustering settings, as well as an intriguing connection to the famous Grothendieck inequality. It is approximable to within a factor of O(log n), and known to be NP-hard to approximate within any factor better than 13/110 - \\varepsilon for all \\varepsilon > O. We show showthat it is quasi-NP-hard to approximate to a factor better than O(Log^\\gamman) for some \\gamma > 0.The integrality gap of the natural semide?nite relaxation for this problem is known as the Grothendieck constant the complete graph, and known to be \\theta (\\log n). The proof this fact was nonconstructive, and did not yield an explicit problem instance where this integrality gap is achieved. Our techniques yield an explicit instance for which the integrality gap is \\Omega (\\frac{{\\log n}}{{\\log \\log n}}), essentially answering one of the open problems of Alon et al. [AMMN].", :doc-id "On Non-Approximability for Quadratic Programs. 2005  ,  ,  ,  ,  "}, 2891923 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2891923, :key "journals/siamjo/Beck07", :title "Quadratic Matrix Programming.", :abstract "We introduce and study a special class of nonconvex quadratic problems in which the objective and constraint functions have the form $f(\\boldmath $X$)={Tr}(\\boldmath $X$^T \\boldmath $A$ \\boldmath $X$) + 2 Tr(\\boldmath $B$^T \\boldmath $X$) +c, \\boldmath $X$ \\in {\\real R}^{n \\times r}$. The latter formulation is termed quadratic matrix programming (QMP) of order $r$. We construct a specially devised semidefinite relaxation (SDR) and dual for the QMP problem and show that under some mild conditions strong duality holds for QMP problems with at most $r$ constraints. Using a result on the equivalence of two characterizations of the nonnegativity property of quadratic functions of the above form, we are able to compare the constructed SDR and dual problems to other known SDRs and dual formulations of the problem. An application to robust least squares problems is discussed.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 80715, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Amir Beck"}), :year 2007, :venue "SIAM Journal on Optimization", :ncit 44, :string "Quadratic Matrix Programming.. We introduce and study a special class of nonconvex quadratic problems in which the objective and constraint functions have the form $f(\\boldmath $X$)={Tr}(\\boldmath $X$^T \\boldmath $A$ \\boldmath $X$) + 2 Tr(\\boldmath $B$^T \\boldmath $X$) +c, \\boldmath $X$ \\in {\\real R}^{n \\times r}$. The latter formulation is termed quadratic matrix programming (QMP) of order $r$. We construct a specially devised semidefinite relaxation (SDR) and dual for the QMP problem and show that under some mild conditions strong duality holds for QMP problems with at most $r$ constraints. Using a result on the equivalence of two characterizations of the nonnegativity property of quadratic functions of the above form, we are able to compare the constructed SDR and dual problems to other known SDRs and dual formulations of the problem. An application to robust least squares problems is discussed.", :doc-id "Quadratic Matrix Programming. 2007  "}, 3765427 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3765427, :key "conf/wea/BuchheimT13a", :title "Separable Non-convex Underestimators for Binary Quadratic Programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1154132, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Christoph Buchheim"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1328550, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Emiliano Traversi"}), :year 2013, :venue "SEA", :ncit 0, :string "Separable Non-convex Underestimators for Binary Quadratic Programming.. ", :doc-id "Separable Non-convex Underestimators for Binary Quadratic Programming. 2013  ,  "}, 210356 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 210356, :key "conf/focs/CharikarW04", :title "Maximizing Quadratic Programs: Extending Grothendieck's Inequality.", :abstract "This paper considers the following type of quadratic programming problem. Given an arbitrary matrix A, whose diagonal elements are zero, find x ¿ {-1, 1}^n such that x^TAx is maximized. Our approximation algorithm for this problem uses the canonical semidefinite relaxation and returns a solution whose ratio to the optimum is in ¿(1/log n). This quadratic programming problem can be seen as an extension to that of maximizing x^TAy (where y's components are also ±1). Grothendieck's inequality states that the ratio of the optimum value of the latter problem to the optimum of its canonical semidefinite relaxation is bounded below by a constant. The study of this type of quadratic program arose from a desire to approximate the maximum correlation in correlation clustering. Nothing substantive was known about this problem; we present an ¿(1/log n) approximation, based on our quadratic programming algorithm. We can also guarantee that our quadratic programming algorithm returns a solution to the MAXCUT problem that has a significant advantage over a random assignment.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 774064, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Moses Charikar"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 151421, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Anthony Wirth"}), :year 2004, :venue "FOCS", :ncit 106, :string "Maximizing Quadratic Programs: Extending Grothendieck's Inequality.. This paper considers the following type of quadratic programming problem. Given an arbitrary matrix A, whose diagonal elements are zero, find x ¿ {-1, 1}^n such that x^TAx is maximized. Our approximation algorithm for this problem uses the canonical semidefinite relaxation and returns a solution whose ratio to the optimum is in ¿(1/log n). This quadratic programming problem can be seen as an extension to that of maximizing x^TAy (where y's components are also ±1). Grothendieck's inequality states that the ratio of the optimum value of the latter problem to the optimum of its canonical semidefinite relaxation is bounded below by a constant. The study of this type of quadratic program arose from a desire to approximate the maximum correlation in correlation clustering. Nothing substantive was known about this problem; we present an ¿(1/log n) approximation, based on our quadratic programming algorithm. We can also guarantee that our quadratic programming algorithm returns a solution to the MAXCUT problem that has a significant advantage over a random assignment.", :doc-id "Maximizing Quadratic Programs: Extending Grothendieck's Inequality. 2004  ,  "}, 391636 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 391636, :key "conf/ijcai/AmatoBZ07", :title "Solving POMDPs Using Quadratically Constrained Linear Programs.", :abstract "Developing scalable algorithms for solving partially observable Markov decision processes (POMDPs) is an important challenge. One approach that effectively addresses the intractable memory requirements of POMDP algorithms is based on representing POMDP policies as finite-state controllers. In this paper, we illustrate some fundamental disadvantages of existing techniques that use controllers. We then propose a new approach that formulates the problem as a quadratically constrained linear program (QCLP), which defines an optimal controller of a desired size. This representation allows a wide range of powerful nonlinear programming algorithms to be used to solve POMDPs. Although QCLP optimization techniques guarantee only local optimality, the results we obtain using an existing optimization method show significant solution improvement over the state-of-the-art techniques. The results open up promising research directions for solving large POMDPs using nonlinear programming methods.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1043535, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Christopher Amato"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 741446, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Daniel S. Bernstein"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 62126, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Shlomo Zilberstein"}), :year 2007, :venue "IJCAI", :ncit 30, :string "Solving POMDPs Using Quadratically Constrained Linear Programs.. Developing scalable algorithms for solving partially observable Markov decision processes (POMDPs) is an important challenge. One approach that effectively addresses the intractable memory requirements of POMDP algorithms is based on representing POMDP policies as finite-state controllers. In this paper, we illustrate some fundamental disadvantages of existing techniques that use controllers. We then propose a new approach that formulates the problem as a quadratically constrained linear program (QCLP), which defines an optimal controller of a desired size. This representation allows a wide range of powerful nonlinear programming algorithms to be used to solve POMDPs. Although QCLP optimization techniques guarantee only local optimality, the results we obtain using an existing optimization method show significant solution improvement over the state-of-the-art techniques. The results open up promising research directions for solving large POMDPs using nonlinear programming methods.", :doc-id "Solving POMDPs Using Quadratically Constrained Linear Programs. 2007  ,  ,  "}, 918068 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 918068, :key "journals/ijon/ZdunekC08", :title "Nonnegative matrix factorization with quadratic programming.", :abstract "Nonnegative matrix factorization (NMF) solves the following problem: find such nonnegative matrices A@?R\"+^I^x^J and X@?R\"+^J^x^K that Y@?AX, given only Y@?R^I^x^K and the assigned index J (K@?I>=J). Basically, the factorization is achieved by alternating minimization of a given cost function subject to nonnegativity constraints. In the paper, we propose to use quadratic programming (QP) to solve the minimization problems. The Tikhonov regularized squared Euclidean cost function is extended with a logarithmic barrier function (which satisfies nonnegativity constraints), and then using second-order Taylor expansion, a QP problem is formulated. This problem is solved with some trust-region subproblem algorithm. The numerical tests are performed on the blind source separation problems.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 407125, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Rafal Zdunek"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 442845, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Andrzej Cichocki"}), :year 2008, :venue "Neurocomputing", :ncit 22, :string "Nonnegative matrix factorization with quadratic programming.. Nonnegative matrix factorization (NMF) solves the following problem: find such nonnegative matrices A@?R\"+^I^x^J and X@?R\"+^J^x^K that Y@?AX, given only Y@?R^I^x^K and the assigned index J (K@?I>=J). Basically, the factorization is achieved by alternating minimization of a given cost function subject to nonnegativity constraints. In the paper, we propose to use quadratic programming (QP) to solve the minimization problems. The Tikhonov regularized squared Euclidean cost function is extended with a logarithmic barrier function (which satisfies nonnegativity constraints), and then using second-order Taylor expansion, a QP problem is formulated. This problem is solved with some trust-region subproblem algorithm. The numerical tests are performed on the blind source separation problems.", :doc-id "Nonnegative matrix factorization with quadratic programming. 2008  ,  "}, 347157 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 347157, :key "conf/icpr/JiangDL06", :title "Convex Quadratic Programming for Object Localization.", :abstract "We set out an object localization scheme based on a convex programming matching method. The proposed approach is designed to match general objects, especially objects with very little texture, and in strong background clutter; traditional methods have great difficulty in such situations. We propose a convex quadratic programming (CQP) relaxation method to solve the problem more robustly. The CQP relaxation uses a small number of basis points to represent the target point space and therefore can be used in very large scale matching problems. We further propose a successive convexification scheme to improve the matching accuracy. Scale and rotation estimation is integrated as well so that the proposed scheme can be applied to general conditions. Experiments show very promising results for the proposed method in object localization applications.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 439745, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Hao Jiang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1420487, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Mark S. Drew"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 560326, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Ze-Nian Li"}), :year 2006, :venue "ICPR (3)", :ncit 0, :string "Convex Quadratic Programming for Object Localization.. We set out an object localization scheme based on a convex programming matching method. The proposed approach is designed to match general objects, especially objects with very little texture, and in strong background clutter; traditional methods have great difficulty in such situations. We propose a convex quadratic programming (CQP) relaxation method to solve the problem more robustly. The CQP relaxation uses a small number of basis points to represent the target point space and therefore can be used in very large scale matching problems. We further propose a successive convexification scheme to improve the matching accuracy. Scale and rotation estimation is integrated as well so that the proposed scheme can be applied to general conditions. Experiments show very promising results for the proposed method in object localization applications.", :doc-id "Convex Quadratic Programming for Object Localization. 2006  ,  ,  "}, 2936885 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2936885, :key "journals/jgo/Etoa10", :title "Solving convex quadratic bilevel programming problems using an enumeration sequential quadratic programming algorithm.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1595364, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jean Bosco Etoa Etoa"}), :year 2010, :venue "J. Global Optimization", :ncit 0, :string "Solving convex quadratic bilevel programming problems using an enumeration sequential quadratic programming algorithm.. ", :doc-id "Solving convex quadratic bilevel programming problems using an enumeration sequential quadratic programming algorithm. 2010  "}, 1014293 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1014293, :key "journals/mp/VandenbusscheN05", :title "A polyhedral study of nonconvex quadratic programs with box constraints.", :abstract "By reformulating quadratic programs using necessary optimality conditions, we obtain a linear program with complementarity constraints. For the case where the only constraints are bounds on the variables, we study a relaxation based on a subset of the optimality conditions. By characterizing its convex hull, we obtain a large class of valid inequalities. These inequalities are used in a branch-and-cut scheme, see [13].", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1523365, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dieter Vandenbussche"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 623064, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "George L. Nemhauser"}), :year 2005, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 34, :string "A polyhedral study of nonconvex quadratic programs with box constraints.. By reformulating quadratic programs using necessary optimality conditions, we obtain a linear program with complementarity constraints. For the case where the only constraints are bounds on the variables, we study a relaxation based on a subset of the optimality conditions. By characterizing its convex hull, we obtain a large class of valid inequalities. These inequalities are used in a branch-and-cut scheme, see [13].", :doc-id "A polyhedral study of nonconvex quadratic programs with box constraints. 2005  ,  "}, 1162869 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1162869, :key "journals/eor/Ammar09", :title "On fuzzy random multiobjective quadratic programming.", :abs