ls/mor/DingGW11", :title "On Equivalence of Semidefinite Relaxations for Quadratic Matrix Programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1430553, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yichuan Ding"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 527936, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Dongdong Ge"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1235659, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Henry Wolkowicz"}), :year 2011, :venue "Math. Oper. Res.", :ncit 7, :string "On Equivalence of Semidefinite Relaxations for Quadratic Matrix Programming.. ", :doc-id "On Equivalence of Semidefinite Relaxations for Quadratic Matrix Programming. 2011  ,  ,  "}, 1211450 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1211450, :key "conf/isnn/Sun09b", :title "A Revised Neural Network for Solving Quadratic Programming Problems.", :abstract "By selecting an appropriate transformation of the variables in quadratic programming problems with equality constraints , a lower order recurrent neural network for solving higher quadratic programming is presented. The proposed recurrent neural network is globally exponential stability and converges to the optimal solutions of the higher quadratic programming. An op-amp based on the analogue circuit realization of the recurrent neural network is described. The recurrent neural network proposed in the paper is simple in structure, and is more stable and more accuracy for solving the higher quadratic programming than some existed conclusions, especially for the case that the number of decision variables is close to the number of the constraints. An illustrative example is discussed to show us how to design the analogue neural network using the steps proposed in this paper.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1471410, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yinjie Sun"}), :year 2009, :venue "ISNN (3)", :ncit 0, :string "A Revised Neural Network for Solving Quadratic Programming Problems.. By selecting an appropriate transformation of the variables in quadratic programming problems with equality constraints , a lower order recurrent neural network for solving higher quadratic programming is presented. The proposed recurrent neural network is globally exponential stability and converges to the optimal solutions of the higher quadratic programming. An op-amp based on the analogue circuit realization of the recurrent neural network is described. The recurrent neural network proposed in the paper is simple in structure, and is more stable and more accuracy for solving the higher quadratic programming than some existed conclusions, especially for the case that the number of decision variables is close to the number of the constraints. An illustrative example is discussed to show us how to design the analogue neural network using the steps proposed in this paper.", :doc-id "A Revised Neural Network for Solving Quadratic Programming Problems. 2009  "}, 1287610 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1287610, :key "journals/jgo/Anstreicher09", :title "Semidefinite programming versus the reformulation-linearization technique for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming.", :abstract "We consider relaxations for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming (QCQP) based on semidefinite programming (SDP) and the reformulation-linearization technique (RLT). From a theoretical standpoint we show that the addition of a semidefiniteness condition removes a substantial portion of the feasible region corresponding to product terms in the RLT relaxation. On test problems we show that the use of SDP and RLT constraints together can produce bounds that are substantially better than either technique used alone. For highly symmetric problems we also consider the effect of symmetry-breaking based on tightened bounds on variables and/or order constraints.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1013219, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Kurt M. Anstreicher"}), :year 2009, :venue "J. Global Optimization", :ncit 66, :string "Semidefinite programming versus the reformulation-linearization technique for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming.. We consider relaxations for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming (QCQP) based on semidefinite programming (SDP) and the reformulation-linearization technique (RLT). From a theoretical standpoint we show that the addition of a semidefiniteness condition removes a substantial portion of the feasible region corresponding to product terms in the RLT relaxation. On test problems we show that the use of SDP and RLT constraints together can produce bounds that are substantially better than either technique used alone. For highly symmetric problems we also consider the effect of symmetry-breaking based on tightened bounds on variables and/or order constraints.", :doc-id "Semidefinite programming versus the reformulation-linearization technique for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming. 2009  "}, 3457530 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3457530, :key "journals/eor/WangLGH12", :title "Path relinking for unconstrained binary quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 731248, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yang Wang"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1545462, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Zhipeng Lü"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1418536, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Fred Glover"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 474267, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Jin-Kao Hao"}), :year 2012, :venue "European Journal of Operational Research", :ncit 1, :string "Path relinking for unconstrained binary quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "Path relinking for unconstrained binary quadratic programming. 2012  ,  ,  ,  "}, 3160794 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3160794, :key "journals/mp/ZhengSL11", :title "Convex relaxations for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming: matrix cone decomposition and polyhedral approximation.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1483646, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaojin Zheng"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1085608, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Xiaoling Sun"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 118392, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Duan Li"}), :year 2011, :venue "Math. Program.", :ncit 1, :string "Convex relaxations for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming: matrix cone decomposition and polyhedral approximation.. ", :doc-id "Convex relaxations for nonconvex quadratically constrained quadratic programming: matrix cone decomposition and polyhedral approximation. 2011  ,  ,  "}, 1061435 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1061435, :key "journals/siamdm/HagerK99", :title "Graph Partitioning and Continuous Quadratic Programming.", :abstract "A continuous quadratic programming formulation is given for min-cut graph partitioning problems. In these problems, we partition the vertices of a graph into a collection of disjoint sets satisfying specified size constraints, while minimizing the sum of weights of edges connecting vertices in different sets. An optimal solution is related to an eigenvector (Fiedler vector) corresponding to the second smallest eigenvalue of the graph's Laplacian. Necessary and sufficient conditions characterizing local minima of the quadratic program are given. The effect of diagonal perturbations on the number of local minimizers is investigated using a test problem from the literature.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 102556, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "William W. Hager"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 793872, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Yaroslav Krylyuk"}), :year 1999, :venue "SIAM J. Discrete Math.", :ncit 40, :string "Graph Partitioning and Continuous Quadratic Programming.. A continuous quadratic programming formulation is given for min-cut graph partitioning problems. In these problems, we partition the vertices of a graph into a collection of disjoint sets satisfying specified size constraints, while minimizing the sum of weights of edges connecting vertices in different sets. An optimal solution is related to an eigenvector (Fiedler vector) corresponding to the second smallest eigenvalue of the graph's Laplacian. Necessary and sufficient conditions characterizing local minima of the quadratic program are given. The effect of diagonal perturbations on the number of local minimizers is investigated using a test problem from the literature.", :doc-id "Graph Partitioning and Continuous Quadratic Programming. 1999  ,  "}, 3693563 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3693563, :key "journals/ol/PolyakCN13", :title "Dual fast projected gradient method for quadratic programming.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 356513, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Roman A. Polyak"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14413837, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "James Costa"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 14413838, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Saba Neyshabouri"}), :year 2013, :venue "Optimization Letters", :ncit 0, :string "Dual fast projected gradient method for quadratic programming.. ", :doc-id "Dual fast projected gradient method for quadratic programming. 2013  ,  ,  "}, 3309692 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 3309692, :key "journals/ol/KimTY12", :title "Solution existence and stability of quadratically constrained convex quadratic programs.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 408260, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "D. S. Kim"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 341109, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "N. N. Tam"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 219733, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "N. D. Yen"}), :year 2012, :venue "Optimization Letters", :ncit 0, :string "Solution 